nationalism, and decolonization particular to Indigenous contexts. Through the lenses of politics, activism, and culture, the questions at the heart of this collection -- What is at stake in conceptualizing Indigenous feminism? How does feminism relate to Indigenous claims to land and sovereignty? What lessons can we learn from the past? How do Indigenous women engage ongoing violence and social and political marginalization? -- cross disciplinary, national, academic, and activist boundaries to explore deeply the unique political and social positions of Indigenous women. A vital and sophisticated discussion, these timely essays will change the way we think about modern feminism and Indigenous women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarman, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarman, Jean, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDemers, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonaldson, Laura E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmberley, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Katherine Young, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrey, Minnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHilden, Patricia Penn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuhndorf, Shari M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuhndorf, Shari M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKalbfleisch, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuhndorf, 